Url.Abstract: Upgrading Version 7.2 Wizard Applications to 9.0 There are no changes necessary for 8.0 wizard application to run with version 9.0.

Url.Title: Customization of WebServer Applications
Url.Abstract: Customization of WebServer Applications Each WebServer Application has, within the config folder, a single cfserver.ini file and an ini file for each DataView. This section of the ChemOffice WebServer Admin Guide describe the settings in these files and suggest some possible customization options.

Url.Title: INI Configuration Files
Url.Abstract: INI Configuration Files The INI Configuration files are necessary for any WebServer application to function properly. Please refer to the following topics for more information:

Url.Title: Chemoffice.ini Configuration File
Url.Abstract: Chemoffice.ini Configuration File The ChemOffice.ini file is necessary for any ChemOffice WebServer application to function properly. This file gives the WebServer basic information about the applications such as a start path and database names.

Url.Title: GLOBALS
Url.Abstract: GLOBALS This heading and its sub-topics provide various Application INI Settings for the Chemoffice.ini Configuration File. Please refer to the following topics for more information:

Url.Title: ALERT_CDAX_VERSION
Url.Abstract: ALERT_CDAX_VERSION Example: ALERT_CDAX_VERSION=8.0.3 Description: Indicates what the minimum version of the ChemDraw plugin should be used with the software. An alert appears for users using the indicated version or lower when accessing the plugin.

Url.Title: CD_PLUGIN_THRESHOLD
Url.Abstract: CD_PLUGIN_THRESHOLD Example: CD_PLUGIN_THRESHOLD= 5.0 Description: This is an internal settings necessary for the ChemDraw Plugin to function properly.

Url.Title: CD_PLUGIN_DOWNLOAD_PATH
Url.Abstract: CD_PLUGIN_DOWNLOAD_PATH Example: CD_PLUGIN_DOWNLOAD_PATH= /chemoffice/chemoffice_download.asp Description: This is an internal settings necessary for the ChemDraw Plugin to function properly.

Url.Title: APP_NAME
Url.Abstract: APP_NAME Example: APP_NAME= sample Description: name of the application displayed in some parts of the user interface

Url.Title: WIZARD_APPNAMES
Url.Abstract: WIZARD_APPNAMES Example: WIZARD_APPNAMES= MyWizardApp Description: A list of applications created by the Admin Wizard, for use with the ChemOffice WebServer.

Url.Title: CS_SECURITY
Url.Abstract: CS_SECURITY Example: CS_SECURITY= 1 Description: Indicates if CS_SECURITY will be used. A value of 1 means CS_SECUIRTY has been configured, a vale of 0 indicates it has not been configured.

Url.Title: FORCE_ORACLE_SESSION_CURSOR_SHARING
Url.Abstract: FORCE_ORACLE_SESSION_CURSOR_SHARING Example: FORCE_ORACLE_SESSION_CURSOR_SHARING=1 Description: Indicates if cursor charing is used during searching and large data loads. Although the default is zero, in general, this should be turned on (set to 1) in order to improve performance. All versions of Oracle 9i can utilize this feature, but only some versions of Oracle 8i show improvement with this set to 1 (e.g. Windows 8i version shows no improvement so this flag should be set to 0). In general, if you are using Oracle 9i, set this value to 1. If you are using Oracle 8i, set this to 0.

Url.Title: Application Definitions
Url.Abstract: Application Definitions This section of the guide provides ChemBioOffice Enterprise Webserver's application definitions. Please refer to the following topics for more information:

Url.Title: SECTION
Url.Abstract: SECTION Example: SECTION= CO_WEBSERVER_STANDARD Description: The section that the application should be listed under onthe ChemOffice WebServer start page.

Url.Title: DB_NAMES
Url.Abstract: DB_NAMES Example: DB_NAMES=sample Description: The name of the directory containing the forms necessary for proper operation of the application. Editing this value may cause unpredictable behavior.

Url.Title: GLOBAL_SEARCH
Url.Abstract: GLOBAL_SEARCH Example: GLOBAL_SEARCH= 1 Description: Indiacates if the application uses global search (not global login). A value of 1 indicates there is global search, a 0 (or empty) indicates global search is not used.

Url.Title: GLOBAL_SEARCH_DISPLAY_NAME
Url.Abstract: GLOBAL_SEARCH_DISPLAY_NAME Example: GLOBAL_SEARCH_DISPLAY_NAME=ChemRXN Global Search Description: The display name (on the login page) for the link to global searching in the application.

Url.Title: GLOBAL_SEARCH_START_PATH
Url.Abstract: GLOBAL_SEARCH_START_PATH Example: GLOBAL_SEARH_START_PATH="/chemrxn/default.asp?formgroup=global_search_form_group&dbname= chemprep"

Url.Title: SAMPLE_START_PATH
Url.Abstract: <DBNAME>_START_PATH Example: SAMPLE_START_PATH="/sample/default.asp?formgroup=base_form_group&dbname= sample"

Url.Title: SAMPLE_DISPLAY_NAME
Url.Abstract: <DBNAME>_DISPLAY_NAME Example: SAMPLE_START_PATH="/sample/default.asp?formgroup=base_form_group&dbname= sample"

Url.Title: Application INI settings (cfserver.ini)
Url.Abstract: Application INI settings (cfserver.ini) The cfserver.ini file is the application ini file. It specifies the DataViews within the application as well as some application variables. The file defines parameters that allow the ChemOffice WebServer application to find necessary information and how to react in certain situations.

Url.Title: GLOBALS
Url.Abstract: GLOBALS This heading and its sub-topics provide definitions for various Application INI settings for cfserver.ini. Please refer to the following topics for more information:

Url.Title: ADJUST_NETSCAPE_WIDTHS
Url.Abstract: ADJUST_NETSCAPE_WIDTHS Example: ADJUST_NETSCAPE_WIDTHS= 0 Description: Corrects for the differences in widths in Netscape compared to IE. 1 will scale Netscape pages, 0 will not make any changes.

Url.Title: ALLOW_HITLIST_MANAGEMENT
Url.Abstract: ALLOW_HITLIST_MANAGEMENT Example: ALLOW_HITLIST_MANAGEMENT= 1 Description: Determines if hitlist management can be accessed from the application. Hitlist management allows users to add, subtract, create the intersection, and union of hitlists. 1 indicates hitlist management is allowed.

Url.Title: ALLOW_HITLIST_MNGMNT_FG_SELECTOR
Url.Abstract: ALLOW_HITLIST_MNGMNT_FG_SELECTOR Example: ALLOW_HITLIST_MNGMNT_FG_SELECTOR= 1 Description: This is only relavent is cases of a global search. Using hitlist management you can recover and operate on lists that were saved under a given form group. That is, hitlists are formgroup specific so the hitlist dialogs show lists from the currently open formgroup. The exception is global search applications where a global search form deals with multiple form groups simulataneously. If ALLOW_HITLIST_MNGMNT_FG_SELECTOR is set to 1, an additional dropdown in the hitlist management dialog appears to allow you to select which histlist you want to save (the hitlist from which formgroup).

Url.Title: ALLOW_PUBLIC_HITLISTS
Url.Abstract: ALLOW_PUBLIC_HITLISTS Example: ALLOW_PUBLIC_HITLISTS= 1 Description: Determines if saved hitlists can be made public. Making a hitlist public allows all other users of the application to access that hitlist. 1 indicates hitlists can be made public.

Url.Title: ALLOW_PUBLIC_QUERIES
Url.Abstract: ALLOW_PUBLIC_QUERIES Example: ALLOW_PUBLIC_QUERIES= 1 Description: Determines if saved queries can be made public. Making a query public allows all other users of the application to access that query. 1 indicates queries can be made public.

Url.Title: ALLOW_QUERY_MANAGEMENT
Url.Abstract: ALLOW_QUERY_MANAGEMENT Example: ALLOW_QUERY_MANAGEMENT= 1 Description: Determines if query management can be accessed from the application. Query management allows users save and recover queries. 1 indicates query management is allowed.

Url.Title: ALWAYS_DISPLAY_ALERTS
Url.Abstract: ALWAYS_DISPLAY_ALERTS Example: ALWAYS_DISPLAY_ALERTS= 1 Description: Indicates if a user should recieve alerts (e.g. compound was registered). 1 turns on all alerts. 0 removes alerts which are not required.

Url.Title: ANIMATED_GIF_PATH
Url.Abstract: ANIMATED_GIF_PATH Example: ANIMATED_GIF_PATH= "/cfserverasp/source/graphics/processing_Ybvl_Ysh_grey.gif"

Url.Title: BODY_BACKGROUND
Url.Abstract: BODY_BACKGROUND Example: BODY_BACKGROUND= "#FFFFFF" Description: Indiactes the background that should be used for the body section of the page.

Url.Title: BRACKET_IN_STRUC_HANDLING
Url.Abstract: BRACKET_IN_STRUC_HANDLING Example: BRACKET_IN_STRUC_HANDLING= "WARN" Description: Related to brackets entered in the structure window. Brackets are not recognized as having any chemical signifigance. WARN indicates the user will be warned if brackets are used, ALLOW ignores the brackets, DISALLOW does not allow the use of brakets in the structurewindow.

Url.Title: CDX_CACHING
Url.Abstract: CDX_CACHING Example: CDX_CACHING= true Description: If set to True, the application will cache cdx files. Registration system overrides this value internally, so changing the setting will not make a difference in Registration System.

Url.Title: DATE_FORMAT
Url.Abstract: DATE_FORMAT Example: DATE_FORMAT= 8 Description: Indicates which international date format to use. The choices are:

Url.Title: DISPLAY_GIFS_ONLY_FORM_IE
Url.Abstract: DISPLAY_GIFS_ONLY_FORM_IE Example:DISPLAY_GIFS_ONLY_FORM_IE= "0" Description: Indiactes if GIFs should be used instead of CDX in form view in IE. 1 indicates GIFs should be used.

Url.Title: DISPLAY_GIFS_ONLY_FORM_NS
Url.Abstract: DISPLAY_GIFS_ONLY_FORM_NS Example:DISPLAY_GIFS_ONLY_FORM_NS= "0" Description: Indiactes if GIFs should be used instead of CDX in form view in Netscape. 1 indicates GIFs should be used.

Url.Title: DISPLAY_GIFS_ONLY_FORM_NS6
Url.Abstract: DISPLAY_GIFS_ONLY_FORM_NS6 Example:DISPLAY_GIFS_ONLY_FORM_NS6= "0" Description: Indiactes if GIFs should be used instead of CDX in form view in Netscape 6. 1 indicates GIFs should be used.

Url.Title: DISPLAY_GIFS_ONLY_LIST_IE
Url.Abstract: DISPLAY_GIFS_ONLY_LIST_IE Example:DISPLAY_GIFS_ONLY_LIST_IE= "0" Description: Indiactes if GIFs should be used instead of CDX in list view in IE. 1 indicates GIFs should be used.

Url.Title: DISPLAY_GIFS_ONLY_LIST_NS
Url.Abstract: DISPLAY_GIFS_ONLY_LIST_NS Example:DISPLAY_GIFS_ONLY_LIST_NS= "0" Description: Indiactes if GIFs should be used instead of CDX in list view in Netscape. 1 indicates GIFs should be used.

Url.Title: DISPLAY_GIFS_ONLY_LIST_NS6
Url.Abstract: DISPLAY_GIFS_ONLY_LIST_NS6 Example:DISPLAY_GIFS_ONLY_LIST_NS6= "0" Description: Indiactes if GIFs should be used instead of CDX in list view in Netscape 6. 1 indicates GIFs should be used.

Url.Title: ENABLE_DETAIL_VIEW
Url.Abstract: ENABLE_DETAIL_VIEW Example: ENABLE_DETAIL_VIEW= 1 Description: Determines if details view is used an an application. 1 indicates details view is used.

Url.Title: EXPIRE_HITLIST_HISTORY_DAYS
Url.Abstract: EXPIRE_HITLIST_HISTORY_DAYS Example: EXPIRE_HITLIST_HISTORY_DAYS= 30 Description: The value of this setting is in days. After the number of days specified, hitlist history entries are removed.

Url.Title: EXPIRE_QUERY_HISTORY_DAYS
Url.Abstract: EXPIRE_QUERY_HISTORY_DAYS Example: EXPIRE_QUERY_HISTORY_DAYS= 2 Description: The value of this setting is in days. After the number of days specified, queries in the history are removed.

Url.Title: EXPIRE_USER_SETTINGS_DAYS
Url.Abstract: EXPIRE_USER_SETTINGS_DAYS Example: EXPIRE_USER_SETTINGS_DAYS= 365 Description: The value of this setting is in days. After the number of days specified of inactivity, user settings are reset to default settings.

Url.Title: FIELD_SPLIT_CHARACTER
Url.Abstract: FIELD_SPLIT_CHARACTER Example:FIELD_SPLIT_CHARACTER= ";" Description: Used to indicate the delimiter in lists entered into fields. Most useful for a field like Synonym where more then one synonym might be added at once.

Url.Title: FORMULA_FORMAT
Url.Abstract: FORMULA_FORMAT Example: FORMULA_FORMAT= 1 Description: Indicates if super- and sub- scripts should be used when displaying a molecular formula. 0 removes formatting.

Url.Title: GLOBAL_SEARCH_BASE_DB
Url.Abstract: GLOBAL_SEARCH_BASE_DB Example: GLOBAL_SEARCH_BASE_DB= sample Description: An internal setting required for global searching.

Url.Title: GLOBAL_SEARCH_DBS
Url.Abstract: GLOBAL_SEARCH_DBS Example: GLOBAL_SEARCH_DBS= sample Description: An internal setting required for global searching.

Url.Title: HIGHLIGHT_BACKGROUND
Url.Abstract: HIGHLIGHT_BACKGROUND Example: HIGHLIGHT_BACKGROUND="border= ""1"" bordercolor= ""#cc0033""" Description: Color used to make the highlighted border for required fields. Only matters if HIGHLIGHT_REQUIRED_FIELDS=1 .

Url.Title: HIGHLIGHT_REQUIRED_FIELDS
Url.Abstract: HIGHLIGHT_REQUIRED_FIELDS Example: HIGHLIGHT_REQUIRED_FIELDS= 1 Description: 1 indicates required fields (listed in another location in the cfserver.ini) should appear with a border around them in edit mode. 0 indicates no border.

Url.Title: MAIN_WINDOW
Url.Abstract: MAIN_WINDOW Example: MAIN_WINDOW= top.frames["main"] Description: The frame name for the central frame used internally by javascript. Editing this value may cause unpredictable behavior

Url.Title: MARKED_HITS_MAX
Url.Abstract: MARKED_HITS_MAX Example: MARKED_HITS_MAX= "500" Description: Indicates the maximum number of records that are loaded after a search.

Url.Title: NAV_BAR_WINDOW
Url.Abstract: NAV_BAR_WINDOW Example: NAV_BAR_WINDOW= top.frames["navbar"] Description: The frame name for the top most frame used internally by javascript. Editing this value may cause unpredictable behavior

Url.Title: NAV_BUTTONS_GIF_PATH
Url.Abstract: NAV_BUTTONS_GIF_PATH Example: NAV_BUTTONS_GIF_PATH= /cfserverasp/source/graphics/navbuttons/ Description: Default graphics path

Url.Title: NON_CHEMICAL_SUBMIT
Url.Abstract: NON_CHEMICAL_SUBMIT Example: NON_CHEMICAL_SUBMIT= "DISALLOW" Description: Indicates if non chemical information can be used in the structure window. DISALLOW does not allow non-chemical information to be used. ALLOW allows non-chemical information to be entered. PROMPT warns the user that non-chemical information has been entered.

Url.Title: PWD_CANNOT_MATCH_USERNAME
Url.Abstract: PWD_CANNOT_MATCH_USERNAME Example: PWD_CANNOT_MATCH_USERNAME= false Description: Indicates if a password is still valid if it matches the username. Setting to true does not allow a password to match the username. This applies to cs_security passwords only and is found in the cs secuirty cfserver.ini file only.

Url.Title: PWD_ILLEGAL_CHARS
Url.Abstract: PWD_ILLEGAL_CHARS Example: PWD_ILLEGAL_CHARS= [\W] Description: A regular expression defining characters that cannot be in a password. This applies to cs_security passwords only and is found in the cs secuirty cfserver.ini file only. For a description of regular expression syntax, please see: http://msdn.microsoft.com/library/default.asp?url=/library/en-us/script56/html/vspropattern.asp

Url.Title: PWD_ILLEGAL_FIRSTCHAR
Url.Abstract: PWD_ILLEGAL_FIRSTCHAR Example: PWD_ILLEGAL_FIRSTCHAR= [\W] Description: A regular expression defining characters that cannot be used as the first character in a password. This applies to cs_security passwords only and is found in the cs secuirty cfserver.ini file only. For a description of regular expression syntax, please see: http://msdn.microsoft.com/library/default.asp?url=/library/en-us/script56/html/vspropattern.asp

Url.Title: PWD_ILLEGALWORD_LIST
Url.Abstract: PWD_ILLEGALWORD_LIST Example: PWD_ILLEGALWORD_LIST= password,banana Description: A comma delimited list of words that cannot be used as a password. This applies to cs_security passwords only and is found in the cs secuirty cfserver.ini file only.

Url.Title: PWD_MAX_LENGTH
Url.Abstract: PWD_MAX_LENGTH Example: PWD_MAX_LENGTH= 12 Description: The maximum character length for a password. This applies to cs_security passwords only and is found in the cs secuirty cfserver.ini file only.

Url.Title: PWD_MIN_LENGTH
Url.Abstract: PWD_MIN_LENGTH Example: PWD_MIN_LENGTH= 3 Description: The minimum character length for a password. This applies to cs_security passwords only and is found in the cs secuirty cfserver.ini file only.

Url.Title: PWD_MUSTHAVE_CHARS
Url.Abstract: PWD_MUSTHAVE_CHARS Example: PWD_MUSTHAVE_CHARS= [0-9] Description: A regular expression defining characters which must be included in a password. This applies to cs_security passwords only and is found in the cs secuirty cfserver.ini file only. For a description of regular expression syntax, please see: http://msdn.microsoft.com/library/default.asp?url=/library/en-us/script56/html/vspropattern.asp

Url.Title: RESIZE_GIFS
Url.Abstract: RESIZE_GIFS Example: RESIZE_GIFS= 1 Description: Resizes GIFs to be the size of the CDX if set to 1. Applies no scaling if set to 0. Only relevent if one of the DISPLAY_GIFS_ONLY_LIST settings is set to 1.

Url.Title: SEARCH_DEFAULT_PREFS
Url.Abstract: SEARCH_DEFAULT_PREFS Example: SEARCH_DEFAULT_PREFS = S1:true,S2:true,S3:true,S4:true,S5:true,S6:90,S7:true,S8:true,S9:true,S10:true,S11:false,S12:false,S13:false

Url.Title: SHOW_RETRIEVE_ALL_BTN
Url.Abstract: SHOW_RETRIEVE_ALL_BTN Example: SHOW_RETRIEVE_ALL_BTN= 1 Description: Determines if the retrieve all button is displayed in the interface. If the retrieve all button is not displayed, a user will have to perform a search to view records. 1 indicates the retrieve all button is visible.

Url.Title: TEMP_DIR_NAME
Url.Abstract: TEMP_DIR_NAME Example: TEMP_DIR_NAME= CFWTEMP Description: The name of the virtual directory which stores temporary files. Editing this value may cause unpredictable behavior

Url.Title: TEMP_DIR_PATH
Url.Abstract: TEMP_DIR_PATH Example: TEMP_DIR_PATH=C:\Inetpub\wwwroot\ChemOffice\cfwtemp Description: The path to the directory where temporary files are stored. If the installation is not made to the C drive, this must be edited.

Url.Title: USE_SESSION_RECORD_COUNTS
Url.Abstract: USE_SESSION_RECORD_COUNTS Example: USE_SESSION_RECORD_COUNTS= 0 Description: Set to 1 when an application is using settings (like RLS in Registration System) where users are returned record counts according to privileges.

Url.Title: USER_INFO_WINDOW
Url.Abstract: USER_INFO_WINDOW Example: USER_INFO_WINDOW= top.frames["userinfo"] Description: The frame name for the left most frame used internally by javascript. Editing this value may cause unpredictable behavior

Url.Title: USERWINDOWBACKGROUND
Url.Abstract: USERWINDOWBACKGROUND Example: USERWINDOWBACKGROUND= "#FFFFFF" Description: Determines the background gif to be used in the left most frame of the window.

Url.Title: DataView INI settings (e.g. sample.ini)
Url.Abstract:
DataView INI settings (e.g. sample.ini) Each ChemOffice WebServer Application can have more than one dataview. The config folder contains an ini file for the Application (cfserver.ini) and one ini file for each dataview. The dataviews that will load is determined by the list of DB_NAMES stored in the cfserver.ini. This allows enabling and disabling of data view loading. For information about the Application INI file see Application INI settings
.

Url.Title: Adding Alternate Input-Result Forms
Url.Abstract: Adding Alternate Input/Result Forms Often times it is helpful to be able to add customized Input or Result forms for an application.

Url.Title: Adding Tables
Url.Abstract: Adding Tables To add a new table to a pre-exiting data view:

Url.Title: GLOBALS
Url.Abstract: GLOBALS This heading and its sub-topics provide definitions for various DataView INI settings (e.g. sample.ini). Please refer to the following topics for more information:

Url.Title: ABOUT_WINDOW
Url.Abstract:
ABOUT_WINDOW Example: ABOUT_WINDOW=
sample Description: The text that appears in the about window describing the name of the data view.

Url.Title: DISPLAY_NAME
Url.Abstract:
DISPLAY_NAME Example: DISPLAY_NAME=
sample Description: The name used in global search screens to identify the dataview.

Url.Title: MAXHITS
Url.Abstract:
MAXHITS Example: MAXHITS=
100 Description: The number of hits returned before a Get More button will appear.

Url.Title: DB_RECORD_COUNT
Url.Abstract:
DB_RECORD_COUNT Example: DB_RECORD_COUNT=
288 Description: The number of records in the database. This appears in all input and result windows in the upper left corner next to TotalRecords.

Url.Title: DB_TYPE
Url.Abstract:
DB_TYPE Example: DB_TYPE=
STRUC Description: Default: STRUC Options:

Url.Title: MAIN_PAGE
Url.Abstract:
MAIN_PAGE Example: MAIN_PAGE=
0 Description: Determines . 1 indicates . Default: 0 Options: 0 | 1

Url.Title: TABLE_ALIASES
Url.Abstract:
TABLE_ALIASES Example: TABLE_ALIASES=
MolTable,Synonyms_r Description: Names of all table definition sections in the ini file. This list must be comma delimited with no spaces. If the table name is not here, it will not be loaded by the application. Table definition sections describe all the information needed by ChemOffice Webserver for searching tables. See the MOLTABLE and SYNONYMS_R
definitions for more information.

Url.Title: SUBFORM_VIEW_NAMES
Url.Abstract:
SUBFORM_VIEW_NAMES Example: SUBFORM_VIEW_NAMES=
NULL Description: Internal Setting. Default: NULL Options: Should not be edited
.

Url.Title: ADO_CONNECTION_NAMES
Url.Abstract:
ADO_CONNECTION_NAMES Example: ADO_CONNECTION_NAMES=
base_connection Description: Names of all ado connection definition sections in the ini file. This list must be comma delimited with no spaces. If the connection name is not here, it will not be loaded by the application. An ADO definition section describes variables for connecting to data source via ADO. In general there is only the default definition "base_connection_group", since most dataviews access the same database. However, this is flexible and allows more definitions then just the default. ADO_Connection_Names are referenced by individual tables.

Url.Title: TABLE_GROUPS
Url.Abstract:
TABLE_GROUPS Example: TABLE_GROUPS=
base_table_group Description: Name of table group definition sections in the ini file. This must be comma delimited, with no spaces. If the table group names are not here, they will not be loaded by the application. A table group specifies information about the order of searching tables, what the base table (searched via ADO) is and what the molecule table (searched via ChemFinder) is. The majority of applications use the default table group named "base_table_group". Table_groups are referenced by Form_Groups.

Url.Title: FORM_GROUPS
Url.Abstract:
FORM_GROUPS Example: FORM_GROUPS=
base_form_group,basenp_form_group,gs_form_group,add_record_form_group,drill_down_form_group

Url.Title: FIELD_MAP_GROUPS
Url.Abstract: FIELD_MAP_GROUPS Example: FIELD_MAP_GROUPS = gs_field_map_group Description: Names of field map group definition sections in the ini file. This must be comma delimited, wiht no spaces. If the field group names are not here, they will not be loaded by the application. Field Map groups specify field mapping used by global search. If global searching is not used, the FIELD_MAP_GROUPS (default group created by the wizard) can be set to NULL. FIELD_MAP_GROUPS are reference by formgroups.

Url.Title: BASE_CONNECTION
Url.Abstract:
[BASE_CONNECTION] Description: Ado connections specified in the ado_connections section of the globals section reference connection sections else where in the ini file. An ADO_Connection group is referenced by each table alias definition. The keys specify data necessary to create the connection to the database via ado
.

Url.Title: CONN_TYPE
Url.Abstract:
CONN_TYPE Example: CONN_TYPE=
DBQ Description: Specifies the type of connection string. Default: DBQ

Url.Title: CONNECTION_STRING
Url.Abstract:
CONNECTION_STRING Example: CONNECTION_STRING= C:\Inetpub\wwwroot\ChemOffice\sample\database\sample.mdb;Driver= {MicrosoftAccessDriver(*.mdb)};DriverId=25;FIL= MS
Access;

Url.Title: CONNECTION_TIMEOUT
Url.Abstract: CONNECTION_TIMEOUT Example: CONNECTION_TIMEOUT= 30 Description: The amount of time in minutes before a connection will automatically close upon no activity. We suggest 15 to 30 minutes.

Url.Title: COMMAND_TIMEOUT
Url.Abstract: COMMAND_TIMEOUT Example: COMMAND_TIMEOUT= 30 Description: The amount of time in minutes before a command object will automatically close upon no activity. We suggest 15 to 30 minutes.

Url.Title: CONNECTION_USERNAME
Url.Abstract: CONNECTION_USERNAME Example: CONNECTION_USERNAME= "" Description: Contains the username for the connection. See Connection Passwords Tables section under "Connection Options in Dataview INI Files" topic for more information.

Url.Title: CONNECTION_PASSWORD
Url.Abstract: CONNECTION_PASSWORD Example: CONNECTION_PASSWORD= "" Description: Contains the password for the connection. If there is a password and you are using a DBQ or DSN then see the See Connection Passwords Tables section under "Connection Options in Dataview INI Files". The way the password is entered is different for different datasources. Otherwise, this entry are probably left empty.

Url.Title: BASE_CFW_FORM
Url.Abstract:
[BASE_CFW_FORM] Description: ChemFinder connection names specified in
the chem_connections section of the globals section reference connection sections elsewhere in the ini file. If a table contains chemical information stored by ChemFinder then the CHEM_CONNECTION name is referenced by the table definition. The keys specify data necessary to create the ChemFinder connection.

Url.Title: STRUC_ENGINE
Url.Abstract: STRUC_ENGINE Example: STRUC_ENGINE = MOLSERVER Description: Specifies what chemical search engine is used. The only current option is MOLSERVER, soon to be expanded to include the Oracle Cartridge.

Url.Title: STRUC_FORM_NAME
Url.Abstract: STRUC_FORM_NAME Example: STRUC_FORM_NAME = sample Description: The unique portion of the ChemFinder form found in the app/dataview/cfwforms directory. There is both a short and long form. The long form is used for searches the short form is used for retrieving chemicals for display.

Url.Title: STRUC_DB_PATH
Url.Abstract: STRUC_DB_PATH Example: STRUC_DB_PATH = C:\Inetpub\wwwroot\ChemOffice\sample\database\sample.mst Description: The path to the mdb file that ChemFinder uses. Even if you are storing all data in Oracle or SQLServer, ChemFinder still uses an MDB file to link tables.

Url.Title: STRUC_TABLE_NAME
Url.Abstract: STRUC_TABLE_NAME Example: STRUC_TABLE_NAME = MolTable Description: The name of the table that the STRUC_FORM_NAME opens. This is often MOLTABLE, but may differ depending on how the original database structure was created.

Url.Title: BASE_TABLE_GROUP
Url.Abstract: [BASE_TABLE_GROUP] Description: As with other items in the globals section the TABLE_GROUP key specifies individual table groups else where in the ini file. Table Groups specify information about what table is the base table for searching, and what table holds the structures.

Url.Title: BASE_TABLE
Url.Abstract: BASE_TABLE Example: BASE_TABLE = MolTable Description: The name of the table whose ids are returned in a search. This is the base table for the dataview.

Url.Title: MOLECULE_TABLE
Url.Abstract: MOLECULE_TABLE Example: MOLECULE_TABLE = MolTable Description: The name of the table that is searched for checmical data. This may or may not be the base table.

Url.Title: TABLE_SQL_ORDER
Url.Abstract: TABLE_SQL_ORDER Example: TABLE_SQL_ORDER = MolTable,Synonyms_r Description: The order in which the tables are added to a JOIN clause.

Url.Title: MOLTABLE
Url.Abstract: [MOLTABLE] Description: As with other items in the globals section the TABLE_GROUP key specifies individual table groups else where in the ini file. Table Groups specify information about what table is the base table for searching, and what table holds the structures.

Url.Title: SYNONYMS_R
Url.Abstract: [SYNONYMS_R] Description: As with other items in the globals section the TABLE_GROUP key specifies individual table groups else where in the ini file. Table Groups specify information about what table is the base table for searching, and what table holds the structures.

Url.Title: BASE_FORM_GROUP
Url.Abstract:
[BASE_FORM_GROUP] Description: The form groups specified in the key, references individual form group sections elsewhere in the ini file. Form groups are a way for ChemOffice Webserver to specify different input and result forms and functionality via
Form_group_flags.

Url.Title: INPUT_FORM_PATH
Url.Abstract: INPUT_FORM_PATH Example: INPUT_FORM_PATH = sample_input_form.asp Description: Name of the search input form.

Url.Title: INPUT_FORM_MODE
Url.Abstract: INPUT_FORM_MODE Example: INPUT_FORM_MODE = search Description: Mode that is set for the input form. Default: search

Url.Title: RESULT_FORM_PATH
Url.Abstract: RESULT_FORM_PATH Example: RESULT_FORM_PATH = sample_result_list.asp Description: Path to the result form. If you use standard ChemOffice Webserver terminology dataview_name & "_result_list.asp", the single record view is automatically determined as dataview_name & "_form.asp".

Url.Title: RESULT_FORM_MODE
Url.Abstract: RESULT_FORM_MODE Example: RESULT_FORM_MODE = list Description: The view that defaults when returning results. Options are list or edit. Edit is a historical name and means the single record view.

Url.Title: PLUGIN_VALUE
Url.Abstract: PLUGIN_VALUE Example: PLUGIN_VALUE = True Description: If there are structure, molecular weight or formula fields then this must be TRUE indicating that the ChemDraw applet should be written into the html output for the form. If specifying FALSE this means no applet code will be written in the file.

Url.Title: STRUCTURE_FIELDS
Url.Abstract: STRUCTURE_FIELDS Example: STRUCTURE_FIELDS = MolTable.Structure Description: Name of the table and field for the structure field in ChemFinder. For example, this is often MolTable.Structure. This is case sensitive relative to what is put into the input and result form. If no structure is present then enter NULL.

Url.Title: FORM_GROUP_FLAG
Url.Abstract: FORM_GROUP_FLAG Example: FORM_GROUP_FLAG = SINGLE_SEARCH Description: Use SINGLE_SEARCH for standard searching form groups; use "GLOBAL_SEARCH" when the form group is involved in global search functionality.

Url.Title: MW_FIELDS
Url.Abstract: MW_FIELDS Example: MW_FIELDS = MolTable.MolWeight Description: Name of the table and field for the molecular weight field in ChemFinder. This is often MolTable.MolWeight. This is case sensitive relative to what is put into the input and result form. If no structure is present then enter NULL.

Url.Title: FORMULA_FIELDS
Url.Abstract:
FORMULA_FIELDS Example: FORMULA_FIELDS = MolTable.Formula Description: Name of the table and field for the formula field in ChemFinder. This is often MolTable.FORMULA. This is case sensitive relative to what is put into the input and result form. If no structure is present then enter NULL.
.

Url.Title: SEARCHABLE_ADO_FIELDS
Url.Abstract: SEARCHABLE_ADO_FIELDS Example: SEARCHABLE_ADO_FIELDS = MolTable.MOL_ID;1,MolTable.Molname;0,Synonyms_r.SYN_ID;1,Synonyms_r.Synonym_r;0

Url.Title: REQUIRED_FIELDS
Url.Abstract:
REQUIRED_FIELDS Example: REQUIRED_FIELDS = NULL Description: Comma delimited list of required fields in the
form.

Url.Title: SDFILE_FIELDS
Url.Abstract:
SDFILE_FIELDS Example: SDFILE_FIELDS = TABLES:MOLTABLE,SYNONYMS_R Description: Internal
setting.

Url.Title: TABLE_GROUP
Url.Abstract: TABLE_GROUP Example: TABLE_GROUP = base_table_group Description: Name of the table group that this form_group references.

Url.Title: NUM_LIST_VIEW
Url.Abstract: NUM_LIST_VIEW Example: NUM_LIST_VIEW = 5 Description: Number of records displayed in list view by default. Making this value higher then 20 makes output in list view that has structure, mw or formula fields very slow.

Url.Title: BASENP_FORM_GROUP
Url.Abstract:
[BASENP_FORM_GROUP] Description: The form groups specified in the key, references individual form group sections elsewhere in the ini file. Form groups are a way for ChemOffice Webserver to specify different input and result forms and functionality via
Form_group_flags.

Url.Title: ADD_RECORD_FORM_GROUP
Url.Abstract:
[ADD_RECORD_FORM_GROUP] Description: The form groups specified in the key, references individual form group sections elsewhere in the ini file. Form groups are a way for ChemOffice Webserver to specify different input and result forms and functionality via
Form_group_flags.

Url.Title: INNER_HIGHLIGHT_COLOR

Url.Title: INNER_SHADOW_COLOR

Url.Abstract: SHOW_ON_MOUSEOVER Example: SHOW_ON_MOUSEOVER=1 Description: This controls if the menu automatically drops down from the menubar during a mouseover. A value of 1 makes the menu drop down, a value of 0 keeps the menu from dropping down until the menubar item is clicked.

Url.Title: Optimizations for Bulk Loading
Url.Abstract: Optimizations for Bulk Loading This section of the guide provides a high level description of the steps involved in loading a Registry Record into the system, highlights areas where load performance can be improved and provides some specific recommendations.

Url.Title: Read Records from the Source File
Url.Abstract: Read Records from the Source File The client application (ie. COEDataLoader) reads the source data (sdf, Excel…) from the file system to parse the content into local client memory. If the source file type is sdf, then the client will pre-scan all database records in order to establish the data type of each field in the file. The COEDataLoader application allows interrupting this pre-scan. Interrupting the pre-scan can save some time for big data files, but does incur a risk that the application may misidentify the data type of a field. For example if the first few values for a particular data field contain purely numerical values but later values contain string values, then stopping the pre-scan may result in the system incorrectly assuming a numerical data type for a field that contains text values.

Url.Title: Validate Properties Values
Url.Abstract: Validate Properties Values After reading the data file the client validates all custom property data values against the conditions defined in the system configuration. This process is performed as each record is read from file. It does not consume significant time and does not require any optimizations. There is little to be gained removing or simplifying validation rules.

Url.Title: Send Records to Application Server
Url.Abstract: Send Records to Application Server After validation, the prepared Registry Records are transferred from the client to the application server. A fraction of the record load time is consumed by this data transfer step. The highest gain in this step can be achieved by avoiding the cost of moving data between a remote client system and the application server. This can be accomplished by executing the bulk load client from the application server. If the bulk load must be performed from a remote client, there can be modest performance gains by adjusting the ChunkSize parameter in the COEDataLoader application configuration file. This settings determines how name registry records are packaged by the client they are sent to the server. A value of up to 200 may beneficial for client systems that have a high latency connection to the application server. Increasing to a very high value can cause a very large data packet to be sent and could result in errors if the HTTP message size limits established by the application server are exceeded.

Url.Title: Execute Addins
Url.Abstract: Execute Addins The Registration System is highly configurable. It can be extended with Addins that perform additional calculations and validations. Depending on the number and nature of configured Addins, a significant fraction of the total record load time can be consumed in this step. It is therefore possible to significantly reduce bulk load times by disabling unnecessary or slow Addins. This is particularly applicable during legacy data load scenarios, where the incoming data may have already been validated or prepared in the original system and does not significantly benefit from the additional work performed by the Addins.

Url.Title: Chemical Structure Duplicate Check
Url.Abstract: Chemical Structure Duplicate Check This is the key step required to ensure that registered records are chemically de-duplicated. The step involves a query matching the incoming chemical structure against the contents of the REGDB.STRUCTURES.STRUCTURE database column. The query is performed by the CSCartridge. It is critical that a property maintained CSCartridge Index exist on the above column. This step is expected to get gradually slower as the number of records present in the database increases. The time required to perform the structure match is dependent on the duplicate check parameters configured in the Registration System. The duplicate search settings determine whether factors such as stereochemistry, charge, isotopic differences, and tautomerism should be examined in determining potential chemical matches. The default duplicate check settings for the web based Registration application are fairly broad. They may typically flag several existing database records (different stereoisomer, isotopically substituted variation, differently charged structures), which the Registrar will visually inspect in order to choose the most optimal match. These broad duplicate check settings will result in longer query times. For bulk loading scenarios, where the data has already been de-duplicated in the originating system, and where there is no manual intervention by the Registrar to review the potential duplicates, it is better to use narrower match parameters that will result in faster and more targeted matches. In particular, enabling the IDENTITY search parameter will result in the fastest possible load performance.

Url.Title: Extended Duplicate Checking
Url.Abstract: Extended Duplicate Checking This step is only performed if the "Find Custom Field Duplicates" addin is enabled. The step involves a query matching a designated incoming property value against the contents of a corresponding column in a database. The query contains a filter of the form UPPER(<COLUMNNAME>) = UPPER('<PROPERTYVALUE>'). It is therefore critical that the designated database column is indexed using a unique functional index on the UPPER column value.

Url.Source: ../Content/DataLoader/Parse and Insert Records into Oracle Tables.htm
Url.Title: Parse and Insert Records into Oracle Tables
Url.Abstract: Parse and Insert Records into Oracle Tables Once the data has been validated and duplicate checked it must be inserted into Oracle tables. This process involves parsing xml and inserting several data rows into the database. The process is both CPU and disk IO intensive. Significant performance boosts can be obtained during bulk loading by ensuring that the database has been properly configured and dimensioned by an experienced Oracle DBA. In particular, best practices to minimize disk resource contention can have a very positive impact on bulk load scenarios.

Url.Title: Index Chemical Documents with CsCartridge
Url.Abstract: Index Chemical Documents with CsCartridge There are four CSCartridge indexes on the REGDB database. Two of the indexes are only used for application search screens. One is only populated when data is inserted into the fragments table. The last one is used for duplicate check searching when records are inserted in the database.

Url.Title: Disable Refresh of Oracle Materialized Views
Url.Abstract: Disable Refresh of Oracle Materialized Views In systems where the integration between the Chemical Inventory and Registration modules has been enabled, there may be Materialized Views of data inserted into the REGDB tables. By default, these views are configured to update as each row is committed to the database. The process of keeping Materialized Views up-to-date can significantly slow down performance of bulk load operations. It is therefore beneficial to suspend the maintenance of Materialized Views that depend on REGDB data and to refresh them at the end of the load.

Url.Title: Fetch Newly Inserted Record
Url.Abstract: Fetch Newly Inserted Record The final step is to retrieve the newly inserted Registry Record out of the database so that it can be returned to the client for display or logging operations. For systems where Row Level Security has been enabled, the performance of retrieving database records is slightly impacted. For bulk load operations it is therefore beneficial to temporarily disable the RLS feature or to run the load operation using a user account that is exempted from RLS security.

Url.Title: Oracle Optimizer Statistics
Url.Abstract: Oracle Optimizer Statistics As always, Oracle performance is highly dependent on maintaining up-to-data statistics on all database objects in order to allow the Oracle query optimizer to chose the most efficient execution plan. During bulk load operations, the state of the database objects will change significantly as the database starts in a nearly empty state and ends with substantial volume of data in many tables. It is therefore critical to periodically gather optimizer statistics throughout the bulk load process.

Url.Title: Normalized Structure Add-in
Url.Abstract: Normalized Structure Add-in The Normalized Structure add-in is used to examine various drawing styles and determining that they do, in fact, refer to the same physical substance. Normalization differs from tautomer perception in that normalization is restricted to different drawing conventions only.

Url.Title: Structure Aggregation Add-in
Url.Abstract: Structure Aggregation Add-in The Structure Aggregation add-in is used to have an aggregated view of multiple components structures available in the mixture record. The number of aggregated structures that can be viewed in a row depends on the number provided in Add-in's Configuration Edition.

Url.Title: ChemDraw Calculations Add-in
Url.Abstract: ChemDraw Calculations Add-in The ChemDraw Calculations add-in is used to apply ChemDraw control 12 transformations to a given property of the registry. This can calculate the Structure Name, Formula Weight, Molecular Formula and Percent Active. The code is extensible to any kind of transformation/operation provided by the ChemDraw control.

Url.Title: Find Custom Field Duplicates Add-in
Url.Abstract: Find Custom Field Duplicates Add-in The Find Custom Field Duplicates add-in is used to identify duplicates using component or structure identifiers/properties. This can be used in recognizing duplicates if records don’t have structure information.

Url.Title: Salt Stripping Add-in
Url.Abstract: Salt Stripping Add-in The Salt Stripping add-in is used to Remove salts from the base fragment to a pre-defined list of salt fragments.

Url.Title: ChemDraw Chemical Warning Checker
Url.Abstract: ChemDraw Chemical Warning Checker The ChemDraw Chemical Warning Checker Add-in checks for correct chemical syntax of the structure drawn in the structure window. It displays a wavy red box around the questionable object if it finds an error in your structure. It can be configured to check for chemical warnings when the user clicks Submit or Register or both. It also provides you with an option to enable or disable any chemical warning as per your preferences.

Url.Title: Python Property Calculation Add-in
Url.Abstract: Python Property Calculation Add-in The Python Property Calculation is an optional add-in that is used to store calculated values from Chemscript into Registration properties field.

Url.Title: Customizing the Search Forms
Url.Abstract: Customizing the Search Forms You can customize the details that you want to be shown in the search results form for temporary and registered records.

Url.Title: System Settings
Url.Abstract: System Settings The administrator user has the privilege to manage the system settings and configuration in order to specify the Registration's workflow.

Url.Title: Row Level Security
Url.Abstract: Row Level Security The Registration system can be optionally configured to implement project based virtual databases. This option known as “Row Level Security” (RLS) prevents certain users from accessing individual database rows based on their security clearance. Row level security is applied based on associations between users, projects, and registered compounds. A user will only see those registered compounds that are associated with projects to which he/she has been granted permissions.

Url.Title: CHEM_CONNECTION_NAMES
Url.Abstract:
CHEM_CONNECTION_NAMES Example: CHEM_CONNECTION_NAMES=
base_cfw_form Description: Names of all ChemFinder connection definition sections in the ini file. This list must be comma delimited with no spaces. If the connection name is not here, it will not be loaded by the application. A ChemFinder connection definition section describes variables for connecting to ChemFinder for searching of chemical information. The default definition "base_cfw_form" is normally present (unless there is no chemical information). In dataviews that deal with reaction databases, there may be three (or more) definitions, one for the reaction, one for the solvent and one for the catalyst. (e.g.config/chemprep.ini file in the chemrxn application).
